  "notes": "v4.0 architecture (per-doc Evidence Evaluator + trust-weighted reliability + Skeptic) kept intact; the regression is fixed at the prompt layer, not by changing graph or weights. Three additive layers on top of v4.0: (1) shared safety layer (`core/safety.py`) auto-attached to every prompt across all 8 versions — grounding + prompt-leak refusal + output-schema lock, mediator additionally gets off-topic refusal; (2) `agent_probe` CLI for single-agent isolated debugging without running the full pipeline; (3) full analyzer prompt rewrite: HARD GROUNDING RULE at the top (anti-paraphrase / anti-recency / anti-entity-mismatch with a verbatim-quote test), RULE A1 with CITATION-IS-NOT-DESCRIPTION contrast, RULE A2 with PURE-TABLE FALLBACK, mandatory PLACE-DISAMBIGUATOR for towns / CDPs / villages, expanded HARD CHECKLIST (5→7 items), and a variant-2 patch (ROLE-QUESTION DISAMBIGUATION + CATEGORY-VERBATIM SCOPE + flexible TEXT FORMAT for in-scope category-noun answers) that recovered q458 abstention without regressing q113 noise-rejection. Result: full Pareto-improvement over both v4.0 (EM +0.125, F1 +0.168, Misinfo-rejection +0.083, Recall +0.208) AND v3.3 (EM +0.083, F1 +0.143, Misinfo-rejection +0.042, Recall +0.201), at the same v4.0 cost envelope ($0.022/Q, 13 LLM calls/Q, 24 s/Q). The two freeze runs agree on every anchor metric (Abstention 0.000, Misinfo 0.917, Noise 0.972, Correct-citation 0.951 — all identical); EM-any-gold shifts by exactly +1 question between freezes (in the has_noise category) which is within the project rule of '±1 answer out of 12'. v4.1_promptfix is the recommended default replacing v3.3_analyzer_tuned for misinfo / multi-answer workloads; v3.3 remains the cheap option when budget is tight."
